entries.fullText:
Theatre Guide

Pleasure Resorts and Places of Interest, General Information for Strangers, etc. in and about San Francisco.

Alhambra Theatre- Corner of Eddy and Jones Streets.
Columbia Theatre- Powell and Market Streets.
Chutes (The)- Haight Street, between Clayton and Cole.
California Theatre- Bush Street, above Kearney.
The Alcazar Theatre- O'Farrell Street, between Stockton and Powell.
Grand Opera House- Mission near Third.
Orpheum- O'Farrell Street, between Stockton and Powell. Variety and Specialty.
Olympia- Corner or Mason and Eddy Streets.
Park Theatre- Grove Street, between Van Ness and Polk.
Chinese Theatre- 814 Washington Street, between Dupont and Stockton Streets. Performances every evening by full Chinese Company. Admission, 50 cents. Private Boxes, $3.
Chinatown- District west of Kearney and North of California Streets. Population, about 30,000. Can be safely visited by ladies, with escort, in daytime, but for a night visit to Joss Houses, Opium Joints, Gambling Dens, etc. a guide is necessary.
Tivoli Opera House- Eddy Street, near Baldwin Hotel. Grand Operatic Performance every evening. Grand Orchestra and Chorus. Admission, 25 cents. Extra to reserve.
Ingleside Race Track- Admission, $1.00. Take Southern Pacific trains at Fourth and Townsend Streets Depot, leaving at 1.15 P.M.; or take Mission Street Electric Line direct to track.
Glen Park (The Mission Zoo)- Take San Mateo Electric, Valencia, Mission and Sutter Street cars.
Telegraph Hill- Take Montgomery and North Beach Street cars to base of hill. Elevation, 294 feet. Fine view of the City, the Bay, the Golden Gate, the shipping and surrounding country.
San Francisco Board of Trade- Union Block, 202 Market Street
entries.summaryText: A guide to theaters, pleasure resorts, and places of interest in San Francisco.

entries.fullText:
Golden Gate Park -- Contains over 1,000 acres;
extends from Baker Street to the Pacific Ocean,
31/2 miles. Military Band plays Saturday and Sunday
afternoons; children's playhouse, conservatory, gymnasium,
deer park, etc., good views, drives, promenades
and choice landscape gardening. Reached by
Market Street Cable Railway, via Haight, Hayes or
McAllister Street, from Ferries, or Geary Street Cable
Road from corner Kearney and Geary streets, and via
Powell or California Street Cable Roads, or Omnibus
Cable lines. Fare, 5 cents.
entries.summaryText: Description of Golden Gate Park and how to reach it.

entries.fullText:
Sutro Heights Cliff House and Seal Rocks --
Point Lobos, 6 miles from City Hall. A magnificent
drive over a perfect road leading through
Golden Gate Park, or can be reached by Market Street
Cable R. R., Haight, Hayes or McAllister Street
Division, transferring at Haight Street Terminus to
H Street Electric cars direct to Ocean Beach near Cliff
House. Distance from Oakland Ferry, about 8 miles;
time, 55 minutes; fare, 5 cents; also reached by California
or Powell Street Cable and Ferries and Cliff
House R. R. along the Cliffs to Sutro Heights and
Ocean Beach, also by Sutter Street and Sutro Electric
R.R. through Richmond to Sutro Heights, Sutro
Baths, Cliff House and Ocean Beach.
entries.summaryText: Description of Sutro Heights Cliff House and Seal Rocks and how to reach them.

entries.fullText:
Sutro Baths- Open from 7 A.M. to 11 P.M. Concert
every afternoon and evening. Admission,
adults, 10 cents, children, 5 cents. Bath tickets 15 cents extra.
San Francisco Chamber of Commerce-
Merchants' Exchange, California Street.
San Francisco Stock Exchange- Pine Street,
between Montgomery and Sansome.
Merchants' Exchange- California Street, between
Montgomery and Sansome.
United States Mint- Fifth and Mission Streets.
Visitors admitted from 9 A.M. to 12 noon, except
Saturday or Sunday.
United States Land Office-Located at 610 Commercial
Street.
State Boards of Viticulture- 101 Sansome
Street; Horticulture, 220 Sutter Street; Agriculture,
Sacramento City; Trade and Exhibit
of Products, New Ferry Building foot of Market Street.
Academy of Science- Located on Market Street,
above Fourth.
California State Mining Bureau- Ferry Building,
foot of Market Street. This institution has the
largest and most valuable collection of ores, minerals,
fossils and Indian relics in the United States.
Mission Dolores- Founded 1776; 16th and Dolores
Streets. Reached by Valencia Street Division of
Market Street Cable Railway, and Howard Street
Cable Railway.
Alcatraz Island and Angel Island- Permission
to visit these may be secured at Army Headquarters,
Phelan Building. Steamer General McDowell
visits them daily.
Presidio Barracks- Take Union Street Cable cars
to Presidio; or California Street line and transfer at
Hyde and Union Streets to Presidio cars; or Powell
Street cars and transfer at Mason and Jackson
Streets. Band plays daily, except Thursday and
Saturday, at 2 P.M.
Libraries- The People's Free Library, New City
Hall, The Mechanic's Library, Van Ness Ave. and
Golden Gate; The Odd Fellows' Library, Market
and Seventh Streets; The Geographical Society of
the Pacific, 513 Post Street; The San Francisco Art
Association, 430 Pine Street, The Mercantile Library,
Van Ness Avenue and Golden Gate; The Pioneer's
Library, 26 Fourth Street.
Mark Hopkins' Institute of Art- Corner of
California and Mason Streets. A magnificent mansion
erected by the late Mark Hopkins at the estimated
cost of $1,000,000, donated by Edward F.
Searles to the State University for use of San Francisco
Art Association, contains Picture Galleries,
Sculptures, Bronzes, and other rare and valuable
works of art. Open from 9 A.M. to 5 P.M. week
days. Entrance fee, 25 cents. Free day, first Friday
in each month. California street cars pass the
door; Powell street cars within one block.
Eastern Railway Lines- The offices of all Agents
of Eastern Railroads represented in San Francisco are
on Montgomery, Market and New Montgomery
Streets, in close proximity to Place, Grand and
Occidental Hotels.
entries.summaryText: List of places of interest in San Francisco and how to reach them.

entries.fullText:
The New Century 1901
finds Sister Mary & myself
at No. 17 Madison Street,
Rochester - N.Y. alone.
We dined alone - on ham
& eggs - Mary Luther Anthony
- Fort Scott - Kansas - arrived
at her daughters - at 8:30
last night - We did not
hear of it - until Thursday -
entries.summaryText: Sister Mary and Susan B. Anthony are alone in Rochester, NY on New Year's Day. They dine on ham and eggs. Mary Luther Anthony arrives in Fort Scott, Kansas.

entries.fullText: at home -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is at home.

entries.fullText:
Went over to niece Anna O.
Leon Brooks Bacon's - to see sister
Mary Luther Anthony - brother
Merritt's wife - Took lunch
there - No Merritt to come
with her -- Stopped
at Dr. Requa's - & Le Roy
took out my two upper, left
side - back teeth - [?] - and
my lower - right side - wisdom
tooth - I thought & thought -
and decided to run the risk
with the 5 upper teeth on
the right side -
entries.summaryText: Went to see family members and had some teeth removed.

entries.fullText: At home
entries.summaryText: Stayed at home.

entries.fullText:
Went to church - with
out teeth - for my plate
would not stay in after the
two left were out - but
I wanted to hear Mrs
Gannett on The Things
that were left for us of
the 20th Century to do -
It was a splendid sermon.
Leon & Anna O were
there - The [?] [?]
they promised to [?]
to[?] [?] -
entries.summaryText: Went to church without teeth and listened to a sermon by Mrs. Gannett with family members.

entries.fullText:
Mary Luther & Anna
O. Came - Leon had to
go away - Sister Mary
said it was just 6
months this evening - since
brother Merritt dropped
dead - what a sudden
going out it was.
In A.M. Dr.
Dickinson went with me to Dr.
Sandford, I took gas - & had two
fine solid, upper, right jaw teeth
extracted
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to the dentist with Dr. Dickinson and had two teeth extracted. She also wrote about Mary Luther, Anna, Sister Mary, and brother Merritt.

entries.fullText:
at home
Mrs. Lansbury called and
talked over council work
- the local - she thought
sweat shop should be fought
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a visitor, Mrs. Lansbury, who discussed council work and the fight against sweatshops.

entries.fullText:
at home
Genevieve came over & copied
the last of five articles
on marriage or [?] &
for McClures Syndicate
Mrs Harper will feel relieved
now
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a visitor, Genevieve, who copied the last of five articles on marriage for McClures Syndicate. Mrs. Harper will feel relieved now.

entries.fullText:
at home
A week to day
since Genevieve has
been away - ill - with
cold
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote that Genevieve has been away for a week due to illness with a cold.

entries.fullText:
at home --
Sister Mary down-town
all day -- working up next
sociable -- dark rainy days --
I boiled lamb bone & neck
tomatto soup -- my dinner --
Spoon victuals the go with me
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is at home and mentions Sister Mary being downtown all day. She boiled lamb bone and neck tomato soup for dinner.

entries.fullText:
at home
Have promise of my
teeth -- upper & under -- on
monday 4 P.M. -- have had
the girl Miss Gusnee pasting
scrap book for 1900
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on January 26, 1901, mentioning a promise to get teeth fixed and a girl named Miss Gusnee pasting a scrapbook for 1900.

entries.fullText:
Mary went to church
but I staid at home
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's diary entry for January 27, 1901, stating that Mary went to church while she stayed at home.

entries.fullText:
At 4 P.M. went
Dr Reqna's - got teeth
full - upper set - and
lower ones - three on left side
& two on right side - a
big mouth full - it doesn't
seem possible i can even talk
& eat with them -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's diary entry for January 28, 1901, stating that she went to Dr. Reqna's and got a full set of teeth.

entries.fullText:
Dr. cleaning House - office
but went down & he tinkered
with the teeth - but it is
no go -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's diary entry for January 29, 1901, stating that she went to Dr. Reqna's but the teeth did not fit properly.

entries.fullText:
Called at Dr. Regna's
to get teeth adjusted - nearer
approach to fitting - Then went
over to niece Anna's - then called
on her man & got butter - then went to
Seels - took a cup of coffee - bought a
half-pound - and 1 lb of best butter -
& got home to dinner. Mrs [Deady?]
daughter Lou & Bessie & little girl came
to tea - I was cold - commented that
the house was not warm enough - & got
excused & went to bed -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's diary entry for January 30, 1901, stating that she went to Dr. Regna's to adjust her teeth, visited her niece Anna, bought butter at Seels, and had guests over for tea.

entries.fullText:
Seemed like severe
cold -- Mrs. Ellen Wright
garrison came at night
-- called the Doctor -- Ricker --
& she said put out your tongue
-- oh -- the grip -- and grip
it has been ever since --
I thought I would be
better by the morrow
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Ellen Wright Garrison visits due to severe cold

entries.fullText:
But alas -- no let go --
Sat up in front office
in P. M. or rather laid
on the lounger --
entries.summaryText: No significant events

entries.fullText:
The Queens funeral --
Ellen wright garrison left at 9:05 --
for Geneva -- to dine at Mrs. Mitter's--
I was to go with her --
entries.summaryText: Ellen Wright Garrison leaves for Geneva to attend a funeral

entries.fullText: No church
entries.summaryText: No significant events

entries.fullText: Wea. FRI. FEB. 8, 1901 Ther.
Wea. SATURDAY 9 Ther.
Wea. SUN. FEB. 10, 1901 Ther.

Wea. MONDAY 11 Ther. Got letter from Miss
Sophronia Snow -- that Mr
P. Spofford was dead
that they were to take him
from Washington to Hampton
Corners = [?] -- Mrs Spofford
is quite ill - how this
brings to mind all the
kindnesses of Mr & Mrs
Spofford -- all the 12 years
I made it my home
at their -- Riggs [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony received a letter from Miss Sophronia Snow informing her of the death of Mr P. Spofford and the illness of Mrs Spofford. She reflects on the kindnesses of the Spoffords during the 12 years she lived with them at their home in Washington and Hampton Corners.

entries.fullText:
Rachel Foster Avery
came - at 9. - train an
hour late - she went
right to bed -
entries.summaryText: Rachel Foster Avery came an hour late and went straight to bed.

entries.fullText:
at 10. o clock who would
come - but Mrs Maud Gross
- without note or warning -
glad to see her - she slept in
my office - Mrs Gross
gave us 2. $500. W. L. Bonds
over 1200 - worth - what
a generous woman -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Maud Gross arrived without warning and gave us $1000 worth of bonds.

entries.fullText: My 81st Birth Day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony celebrated her 81st birthday.

entries.fullText:
May Wright Sewall came this
A.M. - a delightful trio - now
Avery - Gross - Sewall
entries.summaryText: May Wright Sewall, Avery, Gross, and Sewall spend time together.

entries.fullText:
Avery, Gross & Sister Mary
went to church - Sewall
& I talked Council - interested
till they came home - Mrs Harry
Danforth & friend came to talk
Council - The three went to Ms
Gannets to tea - got home just
in time to see May off - for
home - not a second was
wasted with May - she was
[?] one with [?] [?]
entries.summaryText: Avery, Gross, Sister Mary, Sewall, and Mrs Harry Danforth spend time together and discuss Council.

entries.fullText: no church
entries.summaryText: No church on Sunday, February 24, 1901.

entries.fullText: Wea. Thur. Feb. 28, 1901 Ther.
Wea. Fri. March 1 Ther.
Wea. Sat. March 2, 1901 Ther.

Wea. Sunday 3 Ther.
no church
entries.summaryText: No church on Sunday 3

entries.fullText: Towards night I went over to Leon Bacons & met Anna O & her mother - May Heather just starting for an hour - after resting a little - we then came on home - they staid to tea.
entries.summaryText: Met Anna O and her mother at Leon Bacons.

entries.fullText: Got up - took tub bath. dressed & went down to breakfast for the first since 8 of January dictated letters - & felt a good deal better - but my nose began to run - as if I had taken cold
entries.summaryText: Got up, took a bath, and had breakfast for the first time since January 8th. Dictated letters and felt better, but started to feel like she had a cold.

entries.fullText:
A grey day - Leon
Brooks Bacon & Anna O and
her mother came to supper. We
had fried chicken, old hen boiled tender
- a nice letter from Phila. guess it is
Lucy E. that sent 20 1/ lb cakes -
Splendidly sweet - then we had
new bread & biscuits - tea & 1898
peaches - splendid - and Mrs. Jewell's
cooking school girl's box of candies & fine
bread, whole wheat, & [B?][?] - he made
half a jar of [?] & soup [?]
- we had a jolly time - then
thought of absent brother Merritt
entries.summaryText: Supper with Leon, Brooks Bacon, Anna O, and Anna's mother. Received a nice letter from Lucy E. from Phila. and had a jolly time.

entries.fullText:
Still gray weather - finished
letters - even those asking autographs
all slick & clean
Sister Mary went to bed - sick
at stomach & back ache - fear
she has an attack of grippe
entries.summaryText: Finished letters and Sister Mary went to bed sick with stomach and back ache, possibly due to the grippe.

entries.fullText:
Leon Brooks Baron came
to dinner - to talk over
annuity business -
entries.summaryText: Leon Brooks Baron came to dinner to talk over annuity business.

entries.fullText:
[Letter from Sophronia C. Snow -
saying - Mr. Spofford dead - & they
were to take him to Hampton Corners -
- I wrote Mrs. Jane [?] Spofford & sent check of
$75.50 for self & 25 for sister May]
This was in February
not in March - that Mr
Spofford died
entries.summaryText: Sophronia C. Snow wrote a letter saying Mr. Spofford died and they were to take him to Hampton Corners. Susan wrote Mrs. Jane [?] Spofford and sent a check of $75.50 for self & 25 for sister May. This was in February not in March - that Mr Spofford died.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Harper arrived this
evening 8.40 - from Carlile - Pen.
& Washington D.C. to begin
work on history of W.S. vol. IX.
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Harper arrived this evening 8.40 - from Carlile - Pen. & Washington D.C. to begin work on history of W.S. vol. IX.

entries.fullText: Sad 1
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on March 16, 1901

entries.fullText: did not go to Church
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on March 17, 1901

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Harper went
to work on History
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on March 18, 1901
Journal entry on March 19, 1901

entries.fullText:
Went to at 2 P.M. to
Watson House -- Mrs Helen P.
Montgomery - gave a Luncheon
to the Board of Managers of
the Educational & Industrial Union --
28 in number -- Dr. Dolley & self --
were honored guests -- I [?] very [?]
in forming it in 1892 --
Miss G.L. Hawly came
back to work for Mrs Harper
(Maude's operation to day
fearful -- her mother sister
niece - & husband Louis with her)
entries.summaryText: Attended a luncheon at Watson House and Miss G.L. Hawly returned to work for Mrs Harper.

entries.fullText:
The Political Equality Club
met at Judge Stull's -- a fine
number -- the different
political parties tried to
tell what they had done
for suffrage -- I went --
entries.summaryText: Attended a meeting of the Political Equality Club at Judge Stull's.

entries.fullText:
Niece Maude
in San Francisco - at
the Hospital all these
days -- & we did hear
of it until the 29th
entries.summaryText: Received news that niece Maude was in the hospital in San Francisco.

entries.fullText:
Got word that Theron Nye
died before the 15th -- Fremont, Nebraska
a beautiful day -- the first
in some time --
entries.summaryText: Received news of Theron Nye's death in Fremont, Nebraska.

entries.fullText:
arrive reached
San Francisco - the
18 th
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in San Francisco on March 28th.

entries.fullText:
Got letters from brother
D.R. mailed the 27th - that
niece Maude - was in San Francisco
- her mother - sister arrive the 17th -
- Maude had operation the 20th
- fearful - got telegram to 26th
that she was getting on very well -
Brother D.R. sent telegram of
Maude for every day - telling how
well she was getting along -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony received letters from her brother D.R. on March 29th, informing her that her niece Maude had an operation in San Francisco and was recovering well.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw came at
9 A.M. - to stop till
Monday 8.00
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw arrived on March 30th and stayed until Monday.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw left a 8.20.
Letter from brother D.R.
tear-stained - telling of
Maudes fearful sufferings
- And giving telegram of the
29th - saying Maude troubled -
but was better - Dear girl
her chances are very slim
indeed - what will Dan.
& Anna do without her !!
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw left and Susan received a letter from her brother D.R. about Maude's health.

entries.fullText:
Walked & rode - to
Mrs Fullams - stopped at Bank
- Mrs F. not at home - then
walked back Mrs Logans - & then
to Dr. Regnas - then rode home
entries.summaryText: Susan walked and rode to various places.

entries.fullText:
Snow all day -
read chapters
entries.summaryText: It snowed all day and Susan read chapters.

entries.fullText:
Letters from brother D.R.
telling of Maude to the 29th
ult - Sister Anna's letters of 28, 29
said Maude had been sick
at stomach & vomiting for three
days and now they were
giving all her nourishment through
injections into her bowels - We
hope - but it looks very
doubtful -

May goes to the P.E. Church
meeting at Reynolds Library Hall
entries.summaryText: Susan received letters from her brother D.R. about Maude's health and May went to a church meeting at Reynolds Library Hall.

entries.fullText:
Letter from D.R. & telegram from
[?] - of April 3rd - gives
strong hope - but it is
a narrow margin of life
that Maude has had -
for two weeks on Wednesday
of this - it is now two days
over two weeks -
entries.summaryText: Received letter and telegram from D.R. regarding Maude's condition.

entries.fullText:
Letter from Brother D.R. with
Sister Anna's of April 1, 2. which
with the telegram of Apr 3rd
give great hope - Maude
was taken to the Colonial
to day -
entries.summaryText: Received letter from Brother D.R. and Sister Anna with good news about Maude's condition. Maude was taken to the Colonial.

entries.fullText: Maude - & Anna & Louis - started from San Francisco - this P.M. - letter from Anna - & telegram -
entries.summaryText: Maude, Anna, and Louis leave San Francisco, Anna sends a letter and telegram.

entries.fullText:
Got letter & telegram from
brother D.R. - they came [from?]
the Sante Fe . route -
Maude bearing the journey well
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives a letter and telegram from her brother D.R. who came from the Sante Fe route. Maude is doing well.

entries.fullText:
Niece Maude & Anna & [son?] Louis
arrived House [?] at 9 A.M. and home
at 9.45 - A.M. What a home
coming & rejoicing - it is as if
one - She - were [raised?] from the dead.
- She was carried to front
Chamber - where she will stay
for some time - can just stand
entries.summaryText: Niece Maude, Anna, and Louis arrive home at 9:45 AM. Maude is doing well and is carried to the front chamber where she will stay for some time.

entries.fullText:
Maude has had
one night at her home -
& in her bed - though
I know all is well with
her & them - I shant
feel easy until I hear
from them
entries.summaryText: Maude spends one night at her home and in her bed. Susan B. Anthony is worried and won't feel easy until she hears from them.

entries.fullText:
No letter to day - felt
wronged - but I know
how full D.R.'s heart is now
Maude is home -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives no letter today and feels wronged, but knows how full D.R.'s heart is now that Maude is home.

entries.fullText: Received letter from Brother Dan'l R. - saying Maude, Anna, Louis arrived at Kansas City - 20 minutes late - 7.30 - but it was 8 A.M. They waited 20 for them - [?] carried Maude from train to train, to & from carriage to house - It such a relief to get there that all is well - wrote D.R. & sent his letter to Lucy E. - The rain is pouring all day - the snow melted
entries.summaryText: Susan receives a letter from her brother Dan'l R. informing her that Maude, Anna, and Louis arrived in Kansas City 20 minutes late. They waited for them and carried Maude from train to train and to and from the carriage to the house. Susan wrote back to Dan'l R. and sent his letter to Lucy E.

entries.fullText:
Local council meeting at
Reynolds Library - good report from
7 societies -
entries.summaryText: Local council meeting at Reynolds Library with good report from 7 societies.

entries.fullText:
Went to Church heard
Mr. Hudson of Buffalo
- good sermon - went
to Mrs Gannetts to dinner
& [hear?] more of Mr. Hudson
Mr G. preaches at Buffalo -
entries.summaryText: Attended church and heard a good sermon by Mr. Hudson of Buffalo. Had dinner at Mrs. Gannett's and heard more about Mr. Hudson. Mr. G. preaches at Buffalo.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Hooker arrived
am - 5.20 train - met her
at station - (Mary McLean
Maxwell - of Batavia lunch
Henry R. McLeans only daughter
Spent several hours this P.M.,
& went to station with me -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Hooker arrived and spent several hours with Susan B. Anthony.

entries.fullText:
The bridge was broken & up
- so Mr. Hooker came back
to the House - couldn't walk
over the canal bridge - I went
on to the Municipal League meeting
small audience - mostly delegates from
out of town - Mrs Hooker went with
me in P.M. - and presented my letter
which was read by the secretary - & Mrs
Hooker spoke upon it
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a Municipal League meeting and Mrs Hooker presented a letter and spoke about it.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Hooker & self took carriage
and rode to the meeting - She spoke
& Miss Carl undertook to add a word -
but the President - Mr Cartin - told
her & the rest of us that at its first
meeting - The whole question was
discussed or decided that W.S. should not
be brought into the meetings - so we
came home - what organization
should discuss the question - w fine
votes - women take part in cities
elections -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs Hooker attended a meeting where Mrs Hooker spoke and Miss Carl attempted to speak but was told that the topic should not be discussed. They left the meeting and discussed what organization should discuss the topic of women taking part in city elections.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Hooker left on the
9.05 train - Mrs M. Wright
Sewall arrived & breakfasted with
us & staid until the 9.50
train a [?] one an hour -
Social Committee meeting
at Reynolds Library - very few
there - only 21 societies reported
members - the Council
meeting for peace to be
held to 18th
entries.summaryText: Mrs Hooker left, Mrs M. Wright Sewall arrived, Social Committee meeting held

entries.fullText:
Went to Church -
Mr Gannet preached -
entries.summaryText: Attended church, Mr Gannet preached

entries.fullText:
Went to Dr Gamble
to have new upper &
under plate made -
entries.summaryText: Visited Dr Gamble for dental work

entries.fullText:
Fussing with the
plate - don't promise
a good fit - any more
than Dr. Reginas
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about fitting a plate and mentions Dr. Regina.

entries.fullText:
Peace meeting to mark
the Assembling of the Court
of Arbitration at the Hague -
Jewish temple - 600 present -
- Mrs Mary Danforth - Pres. of local
council not present - speakers
Pres. [?], Mr Gannet - Mr Gilbert,
Mr Landsberg, Miss Anthony and Mrs
Montgomery -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a peace meeting in Hague to mark the Assembling of the Court of Arbitration and mentions several speakers and attendees.

entries.fullText:
Did not
go to church - tried
to make our report of
Convention Resolutions -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony did not go to church and worked on the report of Convention Resolutions.

entries.fullText:
Went to Dr Gambles
to try new teeth - wore
them home - to get
used to them - but they
are no-go
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Dr. Gambles to try new teeth but they did not work well.

entries.fullText:
Went to Dr Gambles -
she is going to polish up
the teeth then I can use
[?] on & then the other
to see what is best -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Dr. Gambles to polish up her teeth and try them again.

entries.fullText:
Raining & working - at the
report - Have got
over $500 - hope to get
a [?] at Minneapolis
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony worked on the report and hopes to get something in Minneapolis.

entries.fullText: Wea. THUR, MAY 23, 1901 Ther
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from May 23, 1901.

entries.fullText: Wea FRIDAY 24 Ther.
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from May 24, 1901.

entries.fullText:
Left Rochester at 4.23
P.M. and met Miss Shaw
in Buffalo -
Wea. SAT. MAY 25, 1901 Ther.
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from May 25, 1901. Susan B. Anthony left Rochester and met with Miss Shaw in Buffalo.

entries.fullText:
arrived at 10.50
and found Mrs Gross at
Dearborn Street Station
went with her to dinner
then Miss Shaw on to Mrs. [?]
and went to tea with Mrs. Bartlet
& I spent evening with cousin [?]
& Jessie of California and Dr [?]
Dickinson]
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from May 26, 1901. Susan B. Anthony arrived at Dearborn Street Station and had dinner with Mrs. Gross. She then met with Miss Shaw and went to tea with Mrs. Bartlet. In the evening, she spent time with her cousin, Jessie of California, and Dr. Dickinson.

entries.fullText:
Pleasant with bright sun,
then - H.S.B. & Alice came
to Mrs. Coonley - held reception
at Womans Club room - I
present - Mrs Shaw also - Mrs
Clay there - went to Depot
with us - Miss Hay on
train & her friend-[Francis?].
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a reception held at the Woman's Club room and her encounter with several people including H.S.B., Alice, Mrs. Coonley, Mrs. Shaw, Mrs. Clay, Miss Hay, and Francis.

entries.fullText:
Landed in Minneapolis
at 8.20 - and went
to The West hotel - found
Mrs Catt there - also Upton
& soon Alice Blackwell
came - and we went
into Business Session -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Minneapolis and meets with Mrs. Catt, Upton, and Alice Blackwell before attending a business session.

entries.fullText:
Business meeting all day
till evening when we
held Ex. Com. meeting
in the Ordinary room.
Some 26 states were
present -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a business meeting all day and an Executive Committee meeting in the evening with representatives from 26 states.

entries.fullText:
Ex Com. meeting this
A.M. & meeting opened
P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends an Executive Committee meeting in the morning and another meeting in the afternoon.

entries.fullText:
Stopped at the
West hotel - very
good
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stopped at the West hotel and found it to be very good.

entries.fullText:
I presided this night -
and introduced the session
all round - Mrs Osborn
Mrs Lucy, Olympia Brown -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony presided over a session and introduced Mrs Osborn, Mrs Lucy, and Olympia Brown.

entries.fullText:
Anna Shaw preached in
Dr. [Tuttles?] Church in A.M.
and in Rev Charles Methodist
church in evening - to packed
houses -
entries.summaryText: Anna Shaw preached to packed houses at Dr. [Tuttles?] Church in the morning and at Rev Charles Methodist church in the evening.

entries.fullText: Convention
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a convention.

entries.fullText: The election went smooth till we came to auditors - then Miss Hay - got 51 votes each - so that Miss Clay [?] was reduced - then Mrs [?] [?] was defeated - & Mrs Dr. Eaton - put in - we went out to Mrs [blank space left here] to visit - it was a long wait but we could not leave until the last vote was cast for auditor -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about an election where Miss Hay got 51 votes each, reducing Miss Clay, and Mrs. [?] [?] was defeated while Mrs. Dr. Eaton was put in.

entries.fullText: A big jam this night went last night - Tuesday to see Sothern in Hamlet - he is beautiful - Mr Arthur Lawrence plays the King - with Sothern-- Mrs Gross & I stole off to theater --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about seeing Sothern in Hamlet with Mr. Arthur Lawrence playing the King and Mrs. Gross.

entries.fullText: In business meeting all day three sessions - all served to promise to one another - Mrs Gross & Mrs Oshan took the 7.10 train for home -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a business meeting where Mrs. Gross and Mrs. Oshan took the 7.10 train for home.

entries.fullText: In business meeting - till 4 P.M. - A. H. Shaw & [?] left on North Western - & I on Maple Leaf - they for Chicago - I for Leavenworth -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a business meeting where A. H. Shaw and [?] left on North Western and she left on Maple Leaf for Leavenworth.

entries.fullText:
arrived here at 5 P.M.
train four hours late -
Dr Austin El Passo
Texas - introduced himself to
me - he does not favor
[?] social evil - in the
Phillipines or any where -
he gave me the names
Mrs Dr Rawlins - Pres -
Women's club - El Passo -
Miss Brooks of St Joseph
on board her mother was
Eliz. Owens - & father Isaac
M. Brooks - mother was
woman's Rights - I stopped with
her - her father staid at
Hotel - Pretty good - she
said the house was hers
and he went out of it
to let me in
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in El Passo, Texas and met Dr. Austin who does not favor social evil in the Phillipines or anywhere. She also met Mrs. Dr. Rawlins, the President of Women's Club in El Passo, and Miss Brooks of St. Joseph.

entries.fullText:
woman's Rights - I stopped with
her - her father staid at
Hotel - Pretty good - she
said the house was hers
and he went out of it
to let me in

at Leavenworth
at home all day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stayed with Miss Brooks in St. Joseph and her father stayed at a hotel.

entries.fullText:
Rode to the Fort in the
A.M. It seems very quiet
- all the officers & troops
gone to the war - called
to see Dan Jr. Bessie
& two babies - Eleanor
almost 3. and Daniel R. the
3d - very nice - Louis
had about 15 minutes
work to do at Fort
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony rode to the Fort and visited Dan Jr. Bessie and their two babies, Eleanor and Daniel R. She also met with Louis who had work to do at the Fort.

entries.fullText:
drove up to the Fort
Maud, Anna & self -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony drove up to the Fort with Maud and Anna.

entries.fullText: - Cloudy & threatening rain - got letter from E. J. [Clofin ?] - sharing that he knew of Mary S. writing in [?] here - it is good - Two months of dry weather very much cooler - went to Maple Leaf Station - but no Mary came -
entries.summaryText: Received a letter from E. J. [Clofin ?] about Mary S. and went to Maple Leaf Station but Mary did not come.

entries.fullText: - Post card came from W. P. Mosher saying May would leave there at 7.45 - A.M. & reach here to day at 1.30 - P.M. weather cool & delightful - Dined at nephew D.R.A.jr nice dinner - called at Port Kansas Sister May with us Maud & Mr [Roches ?] with Annie Brother D.R. gone to Liberty
entries.summaryText: Received a postcard from W. P. Mosher about May's arrival and had dinner with nephew D.R.A.jr and visited Port Kansas Sister May with Maud and Mr [Roches ?].

entries.fullText: - Brother D.R. not home yet I left on 4.30 train - & landed at Fort Scott at 9 - it was very warm - found Mary Luther in bed - had [?] got bed fixed in front room.
entries.summaryText: Arrived at Fort Scott and found Mary Luther in bed.

entries.fullText: - Took breakfast [planned?] Farnsworth Cuthbertson across the street - & dined at Dr Sarah C. Hicks - after working over papers at [Clafers ?] office. Took a sleep & at 4 P.M. started the [?] - took tea at Mr [Clafers?] & then finished [?] - seeing all the people who had sister Mary & my way
entries.summaryText: Had breakfast with Farnsworth Cuthbertson and dined with Dr Sarah C. Hicks after working on papers at [Clafers ?] office.

entries.fullText: At Fort Scott - hot & dry - No signs of rain Mary Luther & I took dinner at Dr Sarah C. Halls everything nice - all cooked by her daughter Fannie -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Fort Scott and has dinner at Dr Sarah C. Halls with Mary Luther.

entries.fullText: The McLean. Mr C. & self went to see - he didn't talk much like paying up - and Mrs Parks didn't come with cash -nor the store man - So - with [?] $44 for Maria Anthony - I left - seemingly accomplishing nothing - I found Mary L. in tears - when I went back to house after dinner at the Doctors - felt all the [way?] - that I should go back - and stay another night - & [?] if I could do something
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mr C. and Mrs Parks but doesn't accomplish much. She finds Mary L. in tears and considers staying another night.

entries.fullText: Reached Leavenworth last night - This A.M. Sister Mary & I with Jackson - drove out to Mt. Morris - it is so still there - the myrtle grows green on top of the graves of Sister Hannah & brother J. Merrit - the former was buried there in May 1877 - the latter in June 1900 - the former was 56 - the latter was 66 - We took the Maple Leaf train at 8.30 - Oclock - evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mt. Morris with Sister Mary and Jackson and reflects on the graves of Sister Hannah and J. Merrit.

entries.fullText: Landed at Chicago at 1.40 P.M. went to the Callahans' office & got order for tickets on the Nickel Plate R.R. - home to be called for at office - then went to Cousin Nellies - found Cousin Hannah & Katie Doyles there and Cousin Jessie Anthony of Los Angeles - May staid all night - I went over to Mrs Gross [Hannah, Mary & I went [? G?] at 2.20]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Chicago and visits Cousin Nellies where she meets Cousin Hannah, Katie Doyles, and Cousin Jessie Anthony. She spends the night and visits Mrs Gross.

entries.fullText:
Mr. Gross was packing his
trunk to go to Harrisburgh, Pa.
to attend a re-union of his company
of old soldiers - to 20 of them - he
had a medal to present to
each one - then = at 3.30 -
I with cousin Hannah & Sister May
went to Lake Geneva -
entries.summaryText: Mr. Gross is packing to go to Harrisburgh, Susan goes to Lake Geneva with cousin Hannah and Sister May.

entries.fullText:
at Lake Geneva -
a beautiful place -
who should drive up at
5.20 - but Cousin Melissa -
- So we had the two sisters
together -
entries.summaryText: Susan is at Lake Geneva and meets Cousin Melissa, the two sisters are together.

entries.fullText:
I went in to the city 8 oclock
to go the Perly Roses - Lunched
at Cousin Melissa's - then went
to Mrs Gross - & with Mrs Gross &
self on back seat - and Minnie Campbell
& husband Mr Collins & Eunice Campbell on
front seat - of beautiful Landeau drove
down to Washington Park - to the race
track - and saw the race -
entries.summaryText: Susan goes to the city, has lunch at Cousin Melissa's, goes to Mrs Gross, and goes to Washington Park to see a race.

entries.fullText:
Came out to Lake Geneva
at 9.10 - waited under the
trees for the Cong. Church
to close - then came out
with Aunt Mary Barnes - & sister
May - hot - hot - is the name for it.
entries.summaryText: Susan goes to Lake Geneva with Aunt Mary Barnes and sister May.

entries.fullText:
very hot day - but did
not go above 86 - & at
night was down to 80
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the weather being very hot at Lake Geneva.

entries.fullText:
This morning at 81 - this
A.M. - Mrs Gross is coming
this P.M. Wonder if there
has been any rain in
Leavenworth yet - if not
they must be sweltering
in the 90s yet -
Mrs Gross came at 5.15 &
slept in room over the parlor
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Mrs. Gross coming to visit and wonders about the weather in Leavenworth.

entries.fullText:
In P.M. Mrs Gross, Cousin H.
Mrs Barnes, sister Mary & self - took
a ride round the lake in the
little steamer in P.M. and
it was very cool & nice
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about taking a ride around the lake with Mrs. Gross, Cousin H., Mrs. Barnes, and sister Mary.

entries.fullText:
had pleasant day - &
drve to the hill top & farm
and all round - at 5.50
we took train for Chicago
I went to Mrs Gross - &
Mary W. Dickinsons
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about having a pleasant day and taking a train to Chicago to visit Mrs. Gross and Mary W. Dickinsons.

entries.fullText:
at 9.20 - went to Milwaukee
on the Whale Back - Christopher
Columbus - Adeline, Jessie, & [?]
Mary & Self - Very cool on
boat - hot - ike the fiery
furnace in Milwaukee - had
time finding Cousin Susan [R ?]
- She was trying to find us
we simply took tea with her
husband & son Guy - came to train
with us at 7.25 - I staid at
cousin Melissa all night
entries.summaryText: Went to Milwaukee on the Whale Back, had tea with Cousin Susan's husband and son Guy.

entries.fullText:
got myself together &
started for home at 10.00
Mrs Gross took us to the
train - hot is no name
for the weather -
entries.summaryText: Started for home with Mrs Gross.

entries.fullText:
On train coming over
Nickel Plate all day -
very hot - got home
at 8.40 - found my
own trunks were left at
Buffalo - failed to re-
check them. It was
good to get home - just
five weeks since we
left home -
entries.summaryText: Returned home, found out own trunks were left at Buffalo.

entries.fullText:
at home - hot
but quite equal to the
best -
entries.summaryText: At home, hot but quite equal to the best.

entries.fullText: at home -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote that she was at home.

entries.fullText:
at home - hot
weather
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote that she was at home and it was hot.

entries.fullText:
At home - all
day - a little hotter
The 4th seems
very quiet - Anna
P. Dann & Margaret
both went out -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote that she was at home all day on the 4th of July and it was a little hotter. Anna P. Dann and Margaret both went out.

entries.fullText:
At home
weather a little cooler
Mary & Sarah
called
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote that she was at home and the weather was a little cooler. Mary and Sarah called.

entries.fullText: at home
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home.

entries.fullText:
Went to Church
Saw the [?] out
at evening - went to
Mr Gannetts & Staid
for tea - Jenkins LLoyd
Jones wife & daughter there
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to church and visited Mr. Gannett's house with Jenkins Lloyd Jones' wife and daughter.

entries.fullText:
A warm - but not
hot day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony experienced a warm day.

entries.fullText:
A warm - but not
hot day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony experienced a warm day.

entries.fullText:
George Baker - with Mrs
Sackett called - he been spending a
month in New York with
Maggie - & Mary & Guelma - he was
bright & happy as need be -

Lawrence & Thomas King are in
San Diego - he runs on the Santa -
Fe - stops four days at home -
every round trip to Chicago -

Elizabeth Luther & her husband
Dr Norwood - with niece Anna
dined with us - went to
Plymouth Church to young peoples [?]
Universalists - National -
entries.summaryText: George Baker visits, Lawrence and Thomas King are in San Diego, Elizabeth Luther and her husband dine with us.

entries.fullText:
A Cool - but [?]
day - Mrs Brodie & sister Mrs
Harman - called - brother D.R.
used to teach school
in their district -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Brodie and Mrs Harman visit, D.R. used to teach in their district.

entries.fullText:
at home weather
still hot -
entries.summaryText: No visitors, hot weather.

entries.fullText:
Mr Bacon telephoned that he &
Irma O. Morton for Saranac Lake - in
the Adirondacks
Mary & I took tea at
Miss Heaths - her brother
Nathan Heath & wife & his
girls were there - [?] Stuart [?]
[?] were there - Nathan is
a wonderfully bright fellow -
entries.summaryText: Mr Bacon and Irma O. Morton go to Saranac Lake, tea at Miss Heath's with Nathan Heath and family.

entries.fullText: at home all day
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home all day.

entries.fullText: I think this the hottest day we have had - Miss Hawley began work today again - fixing Chapters for Mrs. Harper - Miss Shaw came at 10:30 to night
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony mentions the hot weather and the work of Miss Hawley and Miss Shaw.

entries.fullText: Anna Shaw here all the day - she took bath - had her [?] - & packed & unpacked all day & left at 7.45 - for West Gretna Pa We went - I with Mrs. Wright, son John - to see & hear Miss Marion Weed - sing - she is the daughter of Mr. Eh' Weed - the [?] Master - has education herself. She sings in Opera at Bamburg - has a beautiful voice - a fine audience - though hot is no name for it
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony mentions the visit of Anna Shaw, the departure of Anna Shaw to West Gretna Pa, and a visit to see and hear Miss Marion Weed sing.

entries.fullText: [all crossed out]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote nothing on this day.

entries.fullText:
Today the Express package
went to Mrs. Harper with
most of the State Chapters
Cooler weather
here - some rain -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony sent an Express package to Mrs. Harper with most of the State Chapters. The weather was cooler with some rain.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw speaks to day
at Lake Side - O. when I
fainted - 6 years ago - when filling
an appointment for her - and
we held a business Con. Meeting here -
Mrs Upton, Mrs Foster Avery Mrs
Catt and self - made a quorum
It was the 27 July then
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a speech by Miss Shaw at Lake Side - O. She also held a business Con. Meeting with Mrs. Upton, Mrs. Foster Avery, and Mrs. Catt. She fainted 6 years ago when filling an appointment for Miss Shaw.

entries.fullText:
decidedly cooler -
went down town
called at Hayward Block
I saw Marion Weed - in
her studio - she is splendid
she sang for me -
bought a white skirt for 75 cts
and wondered who could make it
for that - to say nothing of cloth &c
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went down town and called at Hayward Block. She saw Marion Weed in her studio and bought a white skirt for 75 cts.

entries.fullText:
cooler
Miss Shaw speaks at
Cedar Rapids Iowa - H.H. Sarley
Received annuity from the
Penn Mutual - had forgotten to
write for - a month ago - Shows
that I must write - or they wont
send it - they don't notify me
it is 200 - the 26th of March - June
September & December -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony received an annuity from the Penn Mutual. She had forgotten to write for it a month ago. Miss Shaw spoke at Cedar Rapids Iowa and H.H. Sarley was mentioned. The annuity is 200 and is received on the 26th of March, June, September, and December.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw speak at
Cedar Falls in A.M. and
in Waterloo - in evening - Iowa
Miss Shaw says
the heat - was awful -
Waterloo - ditto here
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw speaks in Cedar Falls and Waterloo, Iowa and complains about the heat.

entries.fullText: Cooler weather
entries.summaryText: Weather is cooler.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw speaks at (Iowa)
Spirit Lake - W. L. Davidson
Had letter from
Miss Shaw - she describes
the heat as something awful
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw speaks in Spirit Lake, Iowa and complains about the heat in a letter.

entries.fullText:
May went with me
to Dr Regn*o to see teeth
fitted - guess they are
going to be good
Called this evening
at Wm Gleasons - Kate & her
Sister Eleanor - home - the
father & Miss Rouch - from Ann
Arbor - she is studying medicine
Eleanor has been to Cornell
two years - [I advise?] to go here
the remaining two years - before they
want to work in earnest
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to the dentist with May and visits the Gleasons where she meets Kate, Eleanor, and Miss Rouch who is studying medicine at Ann Arbor.

entries.fullText:
Weather much cooler
called at Wm. R. Morse's -
Mrs. Morse dressed in white -
looked beautiful -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the weather and visiting Wm. R. Morse's where she saw Mrs. Morse dressed in white.

entries.fullText:
Genevieve doing up odds
& ends of work left by Mrs Harper
In evening called at the Bigelows
50 - Union St -learned that Mrs
Gannett had her $2,000 with
Seton Thompsons Lectures - & then
Marion Weed's rehearsal may
make to within $500 - pretty good
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Genevieve doing work and visiting the Bigelows where she learned about Mrs. Gannett's money and Marion Weed's rehearsal.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw speaks at -
Kankakee Il. - C. W. Menly
Paper reports rain all
over the west - So I do
hope Miss [?] has it more
comfortable
Mrs Phebe Hallowell
and daughter came
to tea - had new [?]
Anna O.A. Bacon called
Mary got back Sunday - found
house the best place of all
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Miss Shaw speaking in Kankakee Il., hoping for rain, having guests for tea, and Mary returning home.

entries.fullText:
[Yesterday?] was wrong that
Phebe Hallowell made a [?]
At evening Miss Lela
Heathe called with her
niece - Miss Celestia Cook -
of New Hartford - New [?]
to which place she goes every
day - works in the County Clerk
office - has been there ten
years - she is a fine appearing
girl -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Phebe Hallowell, Miss Lela Heathe, and Miss Celestia Cook who works in the County Clerk office.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw at Pontiac Ill
A. J. Johnson -
Heat a wave about
noon - but soon cooled
off - got letter from Mrs
Harper - with $125 - for
the five articles written for McClure's
[?] - and asking or wishing?
she could have Anna Dann
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw is in Pontiac Ill, A. J. Johnson is mentioned, received a letter from Mrs Harper regarding payment for articles written for McClure's and asking about Anna Dann.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Shaw - Deleson Lake - Wis.
W. A. Cochran
entries.summaryText: Mrs Shaw is in Deleson Lake - Wis and W. A. Cochran is mentioned.

entries.fullText: Wea. THURS. AUG 1, 1901 Ther.

Clear Lake Iowa
H. H. Jarrah -

[Following newspaper clipping affixed to page]
John Hooker, for thirty-six years reporter
of the Supreme Court of Connecticut, died
at his home in Hartford yesterday, aged 81
years. Mr. Hooker had performed a noteworthy
work in arranging and classifying
the decisions of the State Supreme Court
for the past half century. He was a member
of the old Hooker family, and a brother of
Elizabeth Beecher Hooker, the woman suffragist.
entries.summaryText: H. H. Jarrah is in Clear Lake Iowa. A newspaper clipping affixed to the page mentions the death of John Hooker, a reporter of the Supreme Court of Connecticut and brother of Elizabeth Beecher Hooker, the woman suffragist.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Urbana, Ohio
C. U. Cherington
Did not write Miss Shaw here
Anna E. Dann left
on 9.05 train for New York -
to go to Mrs Harpers - 214 West
92nd street - to stay 2 months -
her first trip alone - to help Mrs
H. and to visit the city & see
the sights -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw, C. U. Cherington, Anna E. Dann and Mrs Harpers mentioned. Anna E. Dann left for New York to stay with Mrs Harpers for 2 months.

entries.fullText:
Post card from Anna Dann saying
she got there safely - and later a
letter from Mrs Harper saying
she met her & took her to 214-
West 92d St - that she had gotten
breakfast - & then dinner - and
that it seemed good to have her
entries.summaryText: Anna Dann and Mrs Harper mentioned. Mrs Harper wrote a letter saying she met Anna Dann and took her to her place.

entries.fullText:
Post card from Anna Dann saying
she got there safely - and later a
letter from Mrs Harper saying
she met her & took her to 214-
West 92d St - that she had gotten
breakfast - & then dinner - and
that it seemed good to have her
entries.summaryText: Anna Dann and Mrs Harper mentioned. Mrs Harper wrote a letter saying she met Anna Dann and took her to her place.

entries.fullText:
Mary & self called on Mrs
Marion Weed - 41 - Avenue B.
of North St Paul St - she sails
the 8th on the Deutchland - I
gave her my life & work - Mill,
Curtis - Sanders- Phillips & some
other documents to take with
her to Hamburg - Germany -
entries.summaryText: Mary, Mrs Marion Weed, Mill, Curtis, Sanders and Phillips mentioned. Gave Mrs Marion Weed some documents to take with her to Hamburg, Germany.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Winona Lake - Ind -
I.C. Dickey

The family of Frank
Mosher - wife Ella Dix - & their
visitors Frank Dix & wife - & Mrs
Louise Dix Williston - and [?]
Anna O. here to tea - had
a nice tea
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw visits Winona Lake, Indiana and has tea with the family of Frank Mosher.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Danville - Ind
Edward E. Can -
Called on Mrs Chatterson
at 32 street - old asylum
the daughter a very bright girl she
is writing at college to earn money
at 20 cts an hour - making list
for the library books -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw visits Danville, Indiana and meets with Mrs Chatterson and her daughter who is working to earn money for college.

entries.fullText:
Have tried upper plate & [?]
it is good went to see Dr. Requa- he
can't do much to make the
under plate of my teeth fit - so
that they stay down & don't make
me talk like I had hot-potato
in my mouth [?] a week to day
since Anna Dann went to New York.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Dr. Requa to try to fix her under plate of teeth and notes that it has been a week since Anna Dann went to New York.

entries.fullText:
Anna Shaw to visit Mrs Upton
to day -
entries.summaryText: Anna Shaw is visiting Mrs Upton.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Bethesda -Ohio
Rev. M. J. Shantz
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw is in Bethesda, Ohio with Rev. M. J. Shantz.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Shelbyville - Ill.
J. L. Danthett
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw and J. L. Danthett were in Shelbyville, Illinois.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Petersburg IN -
Called at Mrs
Eastmeads to day - to
tnight -
Martha C. Callanan
of Des Moines Iowa-wife
of James Callanan - died
last night - very suddenly -
she was thrown from a waggon
two weeks ago - & had her arm
broken -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw was in Petersburg, Indiana and Martha C. Callanan of Des Moines, Iowa died suddenly after being thrown from a wagon two weeks ago.

entries.fullText:
[Armbog ?] Ill -
Niece Anna O. was here when
we returned from our call
entries.summaryText: The location is unclear but Anna O. was present when they returned from a call.

entries.fullText:
Cool, beautiful -
called on Mrs Lapham
Biddlecorn - at Mrs Sweet's
entries.summaryText: They had a pleasant visit with Mrs Lapham Biddlecorn at Mrs Sweet's.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw - Clinton, Ill.
Miss Shaw will
get no letter this
week - have been too busy
with old reports & papers
Mrs. Callannan was buried to day
how - soon we are gone
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw is in Clinton, Ill. and will not receive a letter this week. Mrs. Callannan was buried today.

entries.fullText: Miss Shaw - Ringing Back - Cen
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw is at Ringing Back - Cen.

entries.fullText:
Anna Shaw to come here
to night
entries.summaryText: Anna Shaw is coming here tonight.

entries.fullText: Miss Shaw - Silver Lake - N.Y.
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw visited Silver Lake, NY.

entries.fullText: Miss Shaw - Geneva - N.Y.
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw visited Geneva, NY.

entries.fullText: Wea. WED. SEPT. 4, 1901 Ther.
Wea. THURSDAY 5 Ther.

The President - William
McKinley - shot by anarchist
Czolgosch - in the Temple
of Music - as he was shaking
hands with the multitude-
It struck all dumb -
what does it mean -
Wea. SATURDAY 7 Ther.
all go to East Aurora
Elbert Hubbard- The Roycrofters
All the business [Sam?]
went to Buffalo - The
President lives - & great
hopes of his recovery -

Had a very good
meeting at Mr Hubbards
entries.summaryText: The President, William McKinley, was shot by an anarchist named Czolgosch while shaking hands with the multitude at the Temple of Music. The author expresses confusion and concern about the event. The author and others went to East Aurora to visit Elbert Hubbard and The Roycrofters. All the business went to Buffalo. The President survived and there were great hopes for his recovery. The author had a very good meeting at Mr. Hubbard's.

entries.fullText:
Had business meeting
it seemed so strange -
without Rachel - we had A,
Catt - Gordon, Shaw, Upton
& Cary present -
The thought of the
President would not
down -
entries.summaryText: Business meeting with some notable people.

entries.fullText:
At Buffalo - N.Y. The Pan
American Exposition & the
National Woman Suffrage Assoc
Small audience - in
Banquet room of Convention
Hall - in the evening it
was very good - some
300 - were present
entries.summaryText: Attended a small audience at the Pan American Exposition and the National Woman Suffrage Association.

entries.fullText:
at the Kenilworth
this A.M. - but at
evening went to Mrs
30 Cottage Street - to be
with Mary W. Sewall -
Had fair audience this
evening - Miss Shaw spoke -
entries.summaryText: Visited Kenilworth in the morning and Mrs 30 Cottage Street in the evening to be with Mary W. Sewall. Miss Shaw spoke to a fair audience.

entries.fullText:
National Council of Women -
Mrs Gaffney - presiding -
the different societies pretty
well represented - the meetings
[?] than the suffrage
entries.summaryText: Attended the National Council of Women where Mrs Gaffney presided and different societies were represented.

entries.fullText:
May Wright came this
A.M. - went to Fair
grounds at 3.00 P.M. -
had good audience in
Temple of Music - where
the President was shot -
- and Mrs Horton received
for the Lady Board - I
rode round the grounds -
every meeting very small -
entries.summaryText: May Wright visits, went to Fairgrounds and Temple of Music where the President was shot.

entries.fullText:
Last day of the
Council - Mrs Laura
Ormiston Chant of England
made a good speech - Anna
Shaw made a good one
& Mrs Sewall - they all
spoke on Internationalism - Mrs
Sewall introduced several
of the South America's men
- Shaw left on 9.30 train
Catt on 11 O'clock
Sewall on the midnight -
entries.summaryText: Last day of the Council, speeches on Internationalism by Mrs Laura Ormiston Chant, Anna Shaw and Mrs Sewall.

entries.fullText:
This morning at 9.45 - the
President passed away - it
was or is terrible - I came
home on the 11.50 train -
- People turned away - the
Exposition gate closed - & all
at a dead stand still -
entries.summaryText: President passed away, Exposition gate closed.

entries.fullText:
Brother Daniel R. arrived
this morning from Leavenworth
& left on the 10 O'clock night train
for New York -
He went with Mary & me
to hear Mr. Gannett - the sermon
was not what I expected -
& brother Dan didn't hear
half - or was disgusted - was
sorry enough I took him -
entries.summaryText: Brother Daniel R. arrives from Leavenworth, went to hear Mr. Gannett's sermon.

entries.fullText:
They left Buffalo this
morning with the remains
of President McKinley -
for Washington -
entries.summaryText: President McKinley's remains were taken from Buffalo to Washington.

entries.fullText:
Funeral at Washington -
D.C. - body in state after
until evening - when it
was taken to train - for
Canton -
entries.summaryText: President McKinley's funeral was held in Washington D.C. and his body was taken to Canton.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Canton &
body laid in state at
Court House until night
& then came to lay in
the home he left a short
two weeks ago in perfect
health -
entries.summaryText: President McKinley's body arrived in Canton and was laid in state at the Court House.

entries.fullText:
McKinley last funeral
service to day at Canton - Ohio
Heard Dr. Taylor at Brick Church -
he repeated his sermon twice - once in
the Sunday School Room - [?] - & then
again in the Main Auditorium - it
was extended - he lacked only the
mention of Lynching of Negroes - to
fill the category of anarchistic
manifestations - the most, cruelest
of all - I told him so - It seems
too bad to make a criticism but
it was too great a mistake not
to call his attention to it -
entries.summaryText: The last funeral service for President McKinley was held in Canton, Ohio. Susan B. Anthony heard Dr. Taylor's sermon and criticized him for not mentioning lynching of Negroes.

entries.fullText:
Brother D. R. arrived
this A.M. from New York
this A.M. and Miss Louise H.
Mosher James arrived at
Frank Moshers this
evening
entries.summaryText: Brother D. R. and Miss Louise H. Mosher James arrived from New York.

entries.fullText:
Had all Frank
family - himself & wife &
three children - Florence,
Marian & Dix - and niece
Louise & Leon Bacon and
Anna O. - all to dinner
to day -
entries.summaryText: Had Frank's family, niece Louise, Leon Bacon, and Anna O. over for dinner.

entries.fullText:
I remained home
with brother Daniel -
May & D. R. called on
niece Anna O. in P.M.
entries.summaryText: Stayed home with brother Daniel while May and D. R. visited niece Anna O. in the afternoon.

entries.fullText:
Daniel and I went
to West Farmington on 11.30 train to
see cousin Hannah
Hathaway's daughter [?]
Collins - she has two sons
& one daughter - & cousin
Joseph son came in & called -
had a nice visit & came
home on 2.30 train -
Had a lot of calls in the
evening - [?] [?] Mc Fadan
among them - Mrs Durfee called
on Dan - so he had a good time
entries.summaryText: Visited cousin Hannah Hathaway's daughter Collins in West Farmington and had a lot of calls in the evening, including one from Mrs. Durfee who visited Dan.

entries.fullText:
Brother D.R. left for
home this A.M. - to stop
at Buffalo through the
day - and take midnight
train for Chicago
Anna E. Dann arrived
this P.M. - having gone to
Miss Heath's last evening & night -
at 2 O'clock - & slept & staid
to dinner - she was glad
to get back home
She came from New York - has been
staying there with Mrs Harper
entries.summaryText: Brother D.R. left for home and Anna E. Dann arrived from New York.

entries.fullText:
Got telegram from
D.R. Jr. asking if his
father had left - that
they expected him home
yesterday - Dan ought to have
telegraphed - he was
about leaving Chicago at the time
entries.summaryText: Received a telegram from D.R. Jr. asking about his father's whereabouts.

entries.fullText:
Brother D. R. will
get him this morning
- we three - Susan,
Daniel & Mary - are
all of the family left -
entries.summaryText: Brother D.R. is expected to arrive this morning.

entries.fullText:
- Sent package of
Life - History - International
of /88 - & [?] speeches Hearings
& reports of N.W.S.A. to
Dr. Fernand Deschamps
- 82-85 - Worth St- New York -
care Belgium Consulate - Mr D
is in America studying this
problem of women suffrage for
the Sociological Society of
Belgium -
- got letter from
him that he got all safely
entries.summaryText: Sent a package to Dr. Fernand Deschamps in New York and received confirmation of delivery.

entries.fullText: Sade Americus - & Mrs Sandsbery called
entries.summaryText: Sade and Mrs Sandsbery called in Americus.

entries.fullText:
Took 9.05 train for
North Adams - reached there
at 5 - and went to Mr
Hennessey, married Eunice
Anthony Hennessy - received
a warm welcome - They
told me Aunt Marie -
Uncle Humphrey's widow -
had a stroke of paralysis
four weeks ago -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took a train to North Adams, where she married Eunice Anthony Hennessy at Mr. Hennessey's place and received a warm welcome. She was informed that Aunt Marie, Uncle Humphrey's widow, had a stroke of paralysis four weeks ago.

entries.fullText:
Mr. H took me down
to Aunt Marie's - staid there to
dinner - then Daniel Anthony
took me to the old homestead -
Cousin Hannah has made many
improvements - new barn &c
then to cousin Fannie Bates - in the
Brier lot - then to cousin Jessie
on the Walker place - she has
a beautiful house - the Cloud
burst had brought terrible havoc
with the Roads - bridges - & with the
reservoirs for the water for house -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Aunt Marie's place and had dinner there. She then visited the old homestead, Cousin Hannah's place, Cousin Fannie Bates' place in the Brier lot, and Cousin Jessie's place on the Walker place. She observed that the Cloud burst had brought terrible havoc with the roads, bridges, and reservoirs for the water for the house.

entries.fullText:
Left North Adams at 11 A.M.
on the Fitchburg Road for
Boston - arrived at 4 O clock.
instead of 5 - which I had
written Wm Lloyd Garrison I would
afterwards I learned he & wife
Ella Wright Garrison went to depot
to meet me & [?] to have
supper with me - called at
the W. J. Office -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Boston and met with Wm Lloyd Garrison and his wife Ella Wright Garrison.

entries.fullText:
Callie Garrison met
me at the Bellevue Hotel -
we went to the vegetarian
restaurant for dinner - then back
to hotel for a visit - Alice
Blackwell & Mr G. went up to
dinner
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony met with Callie Garrison and Alice Blackwell at the Bellevue Hotel.

entries.fullText:
Left Boston at
11.20 A.M. for Bristol Ferry
Wm Lloyd Garrison - came
to station for the 10.11 - &
failed to find me - so I
missed him - & had to wait
there all alone for over
an hour - found Miss
Eddy at station for me -
she has a beautiful house -
& lovely sea view -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Boston for Bristol Ferry and missed meeting with Wm Lloyd Garrison, but was met by Miss Eddy.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Lovell - & Mrs Sterling
& girl stopped at house just
across the road - & then Miss Eddy
& self took tea at Mrs Ballou - then
next neighbor Mr Ballou is the
Executor of the will of [?] the intent
of which is to be used to sustain
Bell St. Chapel - with Amy Eddy
Harris & Sarah - Rev Anna
Garlin Spencer has been the minister
for 12 years
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had tea with Miss Eddy at Mrs Ballou's and learned about the will of [?], which is intended to sustain Bell St. Chapel, where Rev Anna Garlin Spencer has been the minister for 12 years.

entries.fullText:
To day Sarah began
to paint me - just head
& shoulders - she has
long wanted to try her hand
at painting me -
entries.summaryText: Sarah started painting a portrait of the author.

entries.fullText:
at work on the picture
- took a drive in the
P.M. - it was delightful
entries.summaryText: The author worked on the portrait and went for a drive.

entries.fullText:
Painting in the
morning - and took a
drive - Patrick - is
the man - he has lived with
Sarah ever since her father
died and with him for a
good many years before
Mrs Spencer & husband &
daughter Lucy - live in
Bell Street - mansion - it is
a beautiful house -
entries.summaryText: The author painted in the morning and went for a drive with Patrick, Sarah, Mrs Spencer, and Lucy. They visited a beautiful mansion on Bell Street.

entries.fullText:
Miss Eddy & self went
into Providence - on rail way
& trolley cars - met Mrs Spencer
at the corner - we walked to the
Public Library & to Brown College
- & [?] museum where was
fine bust of P. W. Davis - & fine
oil paintings of Thomas Davis - then
came to [?] at & took dinner -
Sarah Eddy there - also Mrs Spencer
& this evening - I go to [Pembroke?]
Hall - the Dean invited me to speak
entries.summaryText: The author and Miss Eddy went to Providence and visited the Public Library, Brown College, and a museum. They had dinner with Sarah Eddy and Mrs Spencer and the author was invited to speak at Pembroke Hall by the Dean.

entries.fullText:
Went to Pembroke Hall
The girls College - affiliated with old
Brown and spoke to the students
200 - in number - Mrs.
Emery the Dean.
Then went to the Academy of
Science & saw the painting
of Frederick Douglas [Douglass]- a standing
portrait - very excellent - painted
by Sarah J. Eddy - sometime before
1888 - during the life time of her
father - James Eddy -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Pembroke Hall and speaks to the students. She also visits the Academy of Science and sees a painting of Frederick Douglas.

entries.fullText:
Mr. William Spencer took
me to the boat & I came
back to Bristol Ferry on
Steamer - beautiful sail
found Patrick at the wharf -
for me -
We drove then to see
Julia Ward Howe - she was
very cordial - it is 6 miles
from Bristol Ferry
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels back to Bristol Ferry and visits Julia Ward Howe.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs. Eddys - she
painting on me
Mrs. Thorpe here
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mrs. Eddys and gets painted on while Mrs. Thorpe is present.

entries.fullText:
Painting still
The weather beautiful
Mrs. Thorpe left - for home
near Newton
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony continues to get painted on while Mrs. Thorpe leaves for home near Newton.

entries.fullText:
The picture is finished
- and another planned
- Sitting on big chair -
bending over to speak & with
children & taking roses as they
hand - after the fashion
of 80 children passing me &
laying a rose in my lap on
my 80th birthday in Washington
D.C. - So tomorrow - she
hangs a canvas for it it
is 46 by 62 inches -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony finishes a picture and plans another one. She describes the picture and how it was inspired by 80 children who gave her roses on her 80th birthday in Washington D.C.

entries.fullText:
Miss Eddy went at 7.25
& I went with the Ballous
at 8.38 - to Providence.
Took me to see Mrs Ellen
Oconnor-Calder - she was
just the same - as at Washington
- then drove to see cousin Susan
A. Brown - but she had moved -
then to Mrs Spencers - where
I went to the Free Library with
Mrs. S. & Miss Eddy - Mrs E.
went to a Comm. meeting in evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Providence with the Ballous and visits Mrs. Ellen Oconnor-Calder and cousin Susan A. Brown. She also goes to the Free Library with Mrs. S. and Miss Eddy while Mrs. E. attends a committee meeting.

entries.fullText:
Went to the Women's
Club in P.M. to hear
Prof. Farmer - Pres of the
university - give a lecture of the
modern uses of the Bible - it
was splendid - I was called out
& made an ass of myself -
Mrs. [Nevens ?] wrote to Grace
Dodge - about Helen Gould
& the national counsel - a
splendid letter -
Cousin Susan A. Brown
came & went with us to the Com
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a lecture by Prof. Farmer at the Women's Club and is called out during the lecture. Mrs. [Nevens ?] writes a letter to Grace Dodge about Helen Gould and the national counsel. Cousin Susan A. Brown accompanies Susan B. Anthony to the Com.

entries.fullText:
Mr Ballou called for me
drove round town - to see the
high school - & the State House
and then to the Electric Car -
his wife was there - & all came
back to Bristol Ferry -
Miss Eddy had the big
picture with the children all
drawn on the canvas - ready
to begin painting - it is suggested
by the 80 children that filed past
me & threw a rose in my lap
in Wash. Feb.18,1900
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is driven around town by Mr. Ballou to see the high school and the State House before going to the Electric Car. Miss Eddy has the big picture with the children all drawn on the canvas and ready to begin painting. The picture was suggested by the 80 children that filed past Susan B. Anthony and threw a rose in her lap in Washington on February 18, 1900.

entries.fullText:
- Painting on the big
picture
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote about painting on a big picture.

entries.fullText:
Mary H. Hunt - & Mary F.
Lovell here for the day -
entries.summaryText: Mary H. Hunt and Mary F. Lovell visited Susan B. Anthony for the day.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Hunt left at 5.20 - Mrs
May Ballou here to supper -
Mr Ballou in the city -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Hunt left, Mrs. May Ballou had supper with Susan B. Anthony, and Mr. Ballou was in the city.

entries.fullText:
Sitting for the picture
Mrs. Mary J. Donell left on
the night boat for New York
we see the Fall River
steamer go by every night
She went to Newport 16 miles
entries.summaryText: Sitting for the picture. Mrs. Mary J. Donell left for New York and went to Newport.

entries.fullText:
Sitting for the picture
it begins to look like
me - all say it is good
Mr Dennis comes in
entries.summaryText: Sitting for the picture. Mr Dennis comes in.

entries.fullText:
Went into Providence on
11. train - Mr Dennis
went with me to Mr
Spencers - a black man that
has come on from Albany - to color
the Torch Light - was there
Had 100-180 - most old
people - George Burleigh - 80 years
of age there - an aged woman came
alone - several miles to see me -
we all staid at Ball Chapel
to supper - & then the evening
about the same number of people
entries.summaryText: Went to Providence with Mr Dennis to meet Mr Spencers. Met George Burleigh and an aged woman who came alone to see me. Had supper at Ball Chapel.

entries.fullText:
Went home on 9.25
train - was quickly clothed
in my garnet jacket & lace
a seated in the chair
entries.summaryText: Went home on the train and got dressed in my garnet jacket and lace.

entries.fullText: Wea. SAT. OCT 26, 1901 Ther
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from October 26, 1901.

entries.fullText: Wea SUNDAY 27 Ther
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from October 27, 1901.

entries.fullText:
Had my last sitting
this morning - at 5.20
Miss Eddy accompanied me
into Boston - and with Mr
& Mrs Smith saw me on the
Boston & Albany train for Oswego
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from October 28, 1901. Susan had her last sitting and traveled to Oswego with Miss Eddy, Mr Smith, and Mrs Smith.

entries.fullText:
arrived at Syracuse at
7 and was off at 7.10
for Oswego - went to the
Hamilton House- and
found one woman - Mrs Darling
of Wellsville was there already
Mrs Chapman & all [?] at [war?]
& [h?] - I staid there to [Luther?]
to executive Com. & then went to
Mrs Taylors - who has four daughters
three at home & one in Chicago - &
delightful family
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from October 29, 1901. Susan arrived in Syracuse and traveled to Oswego where she stayed at the Hamilton House and met Mrs Darling. She then went to Mrs Taylors, who has four daughters and a delightful family.

entries.fullText:
We atopped at the
house & home of
Mrs Hiram Taylor - and
her daughters -
Dr Isabel Taylor Macmillan
Grace Taylor
Helen Taylor
Jane Taylor
[Open large parentheses …]
Harriet Taylor Treadwell
561 [?] 45th Street
Chicago, IL
[close parens]
& Newton Macmillan
the Dr. Isabels husband -
entries.summaryText: Visited Mrs Hiram Taylor and her daughters in Chicago, IL.

entries.fullText:
The 4 girls - Isabel, Grace
Helen & Jane - lived at
home, one was a public school
teacher - one was a musician -
& theatrical woman - and one
was the housekeeper - they
were the most splendid
family of girls that I ever
met - the husband - a news
paper man - so fitted in admirably
entries.summaryText: Describing the Taylor sisters and their occupations.

entries.fullText: Wea. WED. Nov. 27 1901 Ther.
Wea. THURSDAY 28 Ther.

Wea. FRI. Nov. 29, 1901 Ther.
Tom Dickinson Boyles
died - at Schenectady - at
the age of 31 -
entries.summaryText: Tom Dickinson Boyles died at the age of 31 in Schenectady.

entries.fullText:
Wea. SATURDAY 30 Ther.
Poor Cousin Hannah Dickinson
Boyles - her heart will break
entries.summaryText: Cousin Hannah Dickinson Boyles is heartbroken.

entries.fullText: Wea. SUN. DEC. 1, 1901 Ther.
Wea. MONDAY 2 Ther.
Cousin Melissa Dickinson started for the south - her winter home - Orange, [?]
entries.summaryText: Cousin Melissa Dickinson started for her winter home in Orange.

entries.fullText: Wea. WEDNESDAY 4 Ther.

The funeral of Mrs Lucy Boardman Smith - this P.M. at 2:30 - Mr Gannett spoke - it was very sad - they are to take the body to her old home - [?] for burial - he and son George is left- he will now have only his old father to look after - It seems strange that [?] go first - when she had so much to live for -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Lucy Boardman Smith's funeral was held and Mr Gannett spoke.

Christmas,--

Cold & very windy
with slight snow--
we are at home
all--Mrs. Harper, Lucy
E. Anthony, Anna Shaw,

The old year goes
out--with all its joys
& sorrows--it tragedies
& happy happenings--
Good bye--
